The Warren White House is a historic house in Waltham, Massachusetts.  The -story wood-frame house was built c. 1850â€“54, and is the oldest surviving house on Warren Street, once an important thoroughfare between Waltham and Belmont.  The house has classic Italianate styling, with a symmetrical three-bay facade, wide cornerboards and entablature, and round-arched gable windows.  It was built by Warren White, a wheelwright, on land owned by David White, a farmer, who sold Warren White the property in 1855.
The house was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1989.
